   120	  before we have anything to issue tokens for.)
   121	- **Blob volume = named volume + one-shot `blob-init` mounter.**
   122	  Empirical Compose behavior verified during planning: a
   123	  top-level `volumes:` declaration **does not** cause Compose to
   124	  create the volume unless at least one service mounts it. A
   125	  bare declaration (no mount, no init service) leaves
   126	  `docker volume ls` empty after `compose up`. To make 10a's
   127	  deliverable real, we ship a one-shot `blob-init` busybox
   128	  container that mounts `eden-blob-data` at `/var/lib/eden/blobs`,
   129	  runs `mkdir -p`, and exits 0. `restart: "no"` prevents the
   130	  exited container from looping; `docker compose up --wait`
   131	  semantics for one-shot services were also verified during
   132	  planning — `--wait` returns exit 0 when a one-shot container
   133	  exits 0, so the smoke test gets a clean signal. Downstream
   134	  services in 10b/10d mount the same volume.
   135	- **10a's blob-volume guarantee is "volume exists," not
   136	  "writable by the eventual 10d producer."** `blob-init` runs as
   137	  BusyBox root, and any in-container writability check 10a runs
   138	  is also from a root container — that proves "root can write,"
   139	  which is uninformative for the eventual non-root LLM-worker
   140	  containers in 10d. We deliberately do **not** make a
   141	  uid/gid/perm contract in 10a. 10d picks the user model when
   142	  the first real producer lands and is responsible for any
   143	  ownership/`chmod`/`chown` step it needs. 10a's smoke test
   144	  asserts existence (`docker volume inspect`) and that the
   145	  `blob-init` container exited 0 — nothing more about the volume.
   146	- **Compose file format = `compose.yaml` (no `version:` field).**
   147	  Modern Docker Compose deprecated the top-level `version:` key and
   148	  Docker recommends using just `compose.yaml`. We name the file
   149	  `compose.yaml` (not `docker-compose.yml`) and omit `version:`.
   150	  `docker compose` (v2 plugin, the only supported flavor) accepts
   151	  both filenames; users on extremely old `docker-compose` (v1, EOL)
   152	  may be surprised, and that's an acceptable cost — v1 has been
   153	  unmaintained for 18+ months.
   154	
