   348	
   349	### `reference/compose/healthcheck/smoke.sh`
   350	
   351	Bash script, exits 0 on success. Used by the new CI job and runnable
   352	locally for verification. Behavior:
   353	
   354	```bash
   355	#!/usr/bin/env bash
   356	set -euo pipefail
   357	
   358	# Bring the stack up using .env.example as the source of truth.
   359	# (Copy to a temp .env if invoked from CI to avoid mutating the
   360	# checked-in file.)
   361	TMPENV="$(mktemp)"
   362	trap 'rm -f "$TMPENV"; docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" down -v' EXIT
   363	cp .env.example "$TMPENV"
   364	
   365	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" up -d --wait --wait-timeout 120
   366	
   367	# Assert both long-running services are healthy.
   368	# `--wait` already enforces this, but we re-check for clarity in CI logs.
   369	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" ps
   370	
   371	# Assert all three named volumes were created at compose-up time.
   372	# blob-init mounts eden-blob-data so Compose creates it; postgres and
   373	# gitea mount their own data volumes the usual way. Project-prefixed
   374	# volume names follow the "<project>_<volume>" convention; the project
   375	# name is fixed by `name: eden-reference` in compose.yaml and is also
   376	# echoed below for traceability.
   377	PROJECT="$(docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" \
   378	            config --format json | jq -r '.name')"
   379	test "$PROJECT" = "eden-reference" \
   380	    || { echo "unexpected project name: $PROJECT"; exit 1; }
   381	for vol in eden-postgres-data eden-gitea-data eden-blob-data; do
   382	    docker volume inspect "${PROJECT}_${vol}" >/dev/null
   383	done
   384	
   385	# Confirm blob-init actually exited 0 (--wait would have failed
   386	# otherwise, but re-checking gives a useful CI log line). Using
   387	# `docker inspect` against the explicit container_name avoids
   388	# `docker compose ps --format json` shape variations across Compose
   389	# versions (some emit NDJSON, some emit a JSON array).
   390	test "$(docker inspect --format '{{.State.ExitCode}}' eden-blob-init)" = "0"
   391	
   392	# Assert Postgres is accepting connections (independent of healthcheck).
   393	docker compose -f compose.yaml --env-file "$TMPENV" exec -T postgres \
   394	    pg_isready -U eden -d eden
   395	
   396	# Assert Gitea API responds.
   397	GITEA_PORT="$(grep ^GITEA_HOST_PORT "$TMPENV" | cut -d= -f2)"
   398	curl -fsS "http://localhost:${GITEA_PORT}/api/v1/version" | grep -q '"version":'
   399	
   400	echo "PASS"
   401	```
   402	
   403	Notes:
   404	
   405	- The `trap` ensures teardown runs even on assertion failure, so
   406	  CI runs don't leave dangling volumes.
   407	- `--wait --wait-timeout 120` (Compose v2 feature) makes `up`
   408	  block until every service is healthy or 2min elapses, exiting
   409	  non-zero if any service fails. This is the cleanest way to
   410	  encode "everything came up healthy" in a script.
   411	- The volume name is the standard `<project>_<volume>` Compose
   412	  convention. The script reads the project name from
   413	  `docker compose config` and asserts it equals
   414	  `eden-reference` (matching the `name:` field in `compose.yaml`)
   415	  before applying the prefix, so a future rename of `name:`
   416	  fails the smoke test loudly rather than silently checking
   417	  the wrong volumes.
   418	
   419	### `.github/workflows/ci.yml` — new `compose-smoke` job
   420	
   421	```yaml
   422	  compose-smoke:
   423	    name: compose-smoke
   424	    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
   425	    steps:
   426	      - uses: actions/checkout@v4
   427	      - name: Verify docker compose is available
   428	        run: docker compose version
   429	      - name: Run compose smoke
   430	        working-directory: reference/compose
   431	        run: bash healthcheck/smoke.sh
   432	```
   433	
   434	GitHub Actions' `ubuntu-latest` runners ship with Docker and the
   435	Compose v2 plugin pre-installed; no extra setup needed.
   436	
   437	We do **not** add `compose-smoke` to branch protection in this PR.
   438	Reasoning: the existing required checks (`docs-lint`,
   439	`schema-validity`, `python-lint`, `python-typecheck`, `python-test`,
   440	`schema-parity`) are sufficient to gate a 10a merge; adding
   441	`compose-smoke` to protection on the *same* PR that introduces it
   442	risks a chicken-and-egg if the job is flaky on first run. Add to
   443	protection in 10b once the job has a few clean runs under its belt.
   444	
